    "millsfield:images_texts": [
      "First Man-Powered Flight in Europe\nNovember 12, 1906 • Paris, France\nZAIRE\n• LA CONQUETE DE L'AIR\n70S\n2.00\nBUREAUX\nPHILATEL/S\nTIMEDRAIRES\n12 XI 1984\nPARIS",
      "International Tributes to the History of Flight\nFirst Man-Powered Flight in Europe\nSince the Wright Brothers' success, Europeans had\nThe full-color cachet shows Dumont's plane being\nredoubled their efforts to build a flying machine.\nserviced before flight. The box kite tail extends ahead\nOne of the most enthusiastic designer-pilots was\nof the wings while the gasoline-fueled engine and\nAlberto Santos-Dumont, a dapper Brazilian-born\nthe propeller are mounted behind the pilot. Santos-\naviator living in Paris. In September and October\nDumont can be seen standing in the center of the\n1906, he made preliminary tests of his 14 bis tail-first\nplane.\naircraft.\nThe definitive test came on November 12, 1906.\nWith a crowd of spectators looking on at Bagatelle,\non the outskirts of Paris, Santos-Dumont climbed\naboard his box-kite plane. Photographers and wit-\nMint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued\nby Zaire in 1978. It depicts two pioneer aircraft, the\n14 bis of Alberto Santos-Dumont and the Wright Flyer\nof Americans Orville and Wilbur Wright.\nnesses with measuring devices recorded the mile-\nstone — a flight of 722 feet at 25.65 miles per hour. It\nwas a world's distance and speed record for heavier-\nthan-air craft.\nPostmark: This Cover was postmarked in Paris, France\non November 12, 1984, the exact anniversary of the\nfirst man-powered flight in Europe.\n© Postal Commemorative Society\nPrinted in U.S.A.\n101G. 0510. 011"
    ],
